Maybe I'll go out of my way to spend some of my copious free time getting onto SDC boards. Maybe.<br>
<br>
Some points:<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">*</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Materials of today can work, the plate won't evaporate or even heat up much (from the &quot;Birth&quot; article, active cooling was not necessary);<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">*</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> A limit might be the amount of grease the ship can carry to re-coat the pusher plate between bombs (personally, I think I'd design it to run out of food first, and I'd pack plenty of provisions);<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">*</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Nobody thinks seriously about interstellar, but for interplanetary travel, it beats the hell out of a slow death by privation, isolation, or solar radiation as in any other space drive we can possibly build today or in the near future;<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">*</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Nobody seriously thinks of &quot;tens of thousands of bombs going off in the atmosphere&quot;, and the detractions mentioning such &quot;problems&quot; neatly ignore the space-launch alternatives. There's also the possibility that we could get the pentagon to declassify any useful R&amp;D towards &quot;clean, fusion only&quot; sub-KT bombs, if any. There's also the possibility of using bombs which are designed to limit or eliminate harmful fallout. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>We</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> don't know or can't say for certain, so Orion -even ground launch- must be kept in mind;<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">*</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> EMP is much talked about, but very little reason to link it to Orion except the common thought train &quot;Nukes produce EMP, which is bad... Orion uses Nukes... Orion must be bad.&quot;<br>
Show a single shred of evidence that EMP is a danger with small (&gt;20KT) bombs in or above LEO, which haven't been specifically designed to maximize EMP.<br>
Forget about it. Everything says that it's a problem with extremely large (several MT +) in the upper atmosphere, or much smaller bombs which have been spcifically built to make a strong EMP.<br>
<br>
Good introductory article (note the space-launched ships in the section on Orion, also the bomb detail)<br>
