<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> Materials of today can work, the plate won't evaporate or even heat up much</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I find that a little hard to grasp considering the temperatures created from a nuclear detonation’s fireball that has a tendency to grow quite large in a very short period of time. For example:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Because of the tremendous amounts of energy liberated per unit mass in a nuclear detonation, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>temperatures of several tens of million degrees centigrade develop in the immediate area of the detonation</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->. This is in marked contrast to the few thousand degrees of a conventional explosion. At these very high temperatures the nonfissioned parts of the nuclear weapon are vaporized.<br>
<br>
